[2026-07-01T01:54:29.525+0000] {python.py:237} INFO - Done. Returned value was: A Fast Local Codebase Search Engine in Python with Embeddings and SQLite

Developers are spending more time inside large codebases than ever.

The hard part is rarely opening files. It is finding the exact function, class, SQL fragment, config value, or API call that matters right now.

Keyword search helps until naming drifts. After that, grep starts missing the intent behind a question like:

• “Where do we validate JWT expiration?”
• “Which code writes customer billing events?”
• “What part of the app retries failed webhooks?”

A practical fix is semantic code search: turn code chunks into embeddings, store them locally, and retrieve the most relevant pieces for a natural-language query.

This article builds a small local code search engine in Python.

It runs on your machine, uses SQLite for storage, creates embeddings for code chunks, and returns the most relevant snippets for a query. The result is useful on its own and also works as a retrieval layer for coding assistants, internal tools, and documentation workflows.

⸻

What this solves

A local semantic search layer is useful when you need to:

• search a repository by meaning, not just keywords
• inspect unfamiliar projects faster
• prepare context for a coding agent
• avoid sending private code to a hosted indexing service
• build a lightweight retrieval system without standing up vector infrastructure

This approach is intentionally small.

There is no distributed database, no orchestration layer, and no dependency on a full RAG stack. For many teams, that is a feature.

⸻

How the system works

The pipeline has four parts:

• Walk through a project directory
• Split files into chunks
• Generate an embedding for each chunk
• Store chunks and vectors in SQLite for retrieval

At query time:

• Embed the user query
• Compute similarity against stored vectors
• Return the top matches with file paths and code snippets

For simplicity, we will use a local-friendly design:

• Python
• SQLite
• NumPy
• sentence-transformers

This works well for Python, JavaScript, TypeScript, SQL, YAML, and similar text-heavy repositories.

⸻

Project structure

Create a small project like this:

semantic_code_search/
index_codebase.py
search_codebase.py
requirements.txt

Install dependencies:

python -m pip install sentence-transformers numpy

If you want faster numerical operations, make sure NumPy is installed with a performant build for your platform.

⸻

Design choices that matter

Before writing code, a few decisions shape quality more than people expect.

Chunking strategy

If chunks are too small, you lose context.

If chunks are too large, retrieval becomes noisy.

A good starting point for code is:

• chunk by lines
• keep 40–80 lines per chunk
• overlap by 10–20 lines

This preserves local context around functions and classes.

Metadata

Store more than just text.

Useful metadata includes:

• file path
• chunk index
• start line
• end line
• language or extension
• last modified timestamp

That makes search results easier to inspect and refresh later.

Vector storage

SQLite does not need to be a full vector database to be useful.

For a local project, storing vectors as binary blobs is enough. We can load them into memory during search and compute cosine similarity with NumPy.

⸻

Step 1 — Build the indexer

The indexer scans files, chunks them, embeds them, and stores everything in SQLite.

index_codebase.py

import os
import sqlite3
import hashlib
from pathlib import Path
from typing import List, Tuple
import numpy as np
from sentence_transformers import SentenceTransformer

DB_PATH = "code_index.db"
MODEL_NAME = "sentence-transformers/all-MiniLM-L6-v2"

INCLUDE_EXTENSIONS = {
    ".py", ".js", ".ts", ".tsx", ".jsx",
    ".sql", ".yaml", ".yml", ".json",
    ".md", ".toml", ".ini", ".sh"
}

EXCLUDE_DIRS = {
    ".git", "node_modules", "__pycache__", ".venv",
    "venv", "dist", "build", ".mypy_cache"
}

CHUNK_SIZE = 60
CHUNK_OVERLAP = 15

def sha1_text(text: str) -> str:
    return hashlib.sha1(text.encode("utf-8")).hexdigest()

def init_db(conn: sqlite3.Connection):
    conn.execute("""
        CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS chunks (
            id INTEGER PRIMARY KEY AUTOINCREMENT,
            file_path TEXT NOT NULL,
            chunk_index INTEGER NOT NULL,
            start_line INTEGER NOT NULL,
            end_line INTEGER NOT NULL,
            content TEXT NOT NULL,
            content_hash TEXT NOT NULL,
            embedding BLOB NOT NULL
        )
    """)
    conn.execute("""
        CREATE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_file_path ON chunks(file_path)
    """)
    conn.execute("""
        CREATE UNIQUE INDEX IF NOT EXISTS idx_unique_chunk
        ON chunks(file_path, chunk_index, content_hash)
    """)
    conn.commit()

def should_include_file(path: Path) -> bool:
    return path.suffix.lower() in INCLUDE_EXTENSIONS

def walk_files(root: Path) -> List[Path]:
    files = []
    for dirpath, dirnames, filenames in os.walk(root):
        dirnames[:] = [d for d in dirnames if d not in EXCLUDE_DIRS]
        for filename in filenames:
            path = Path(dirpath) / filename
            if should_include_file(path):
                files.append(path)
    return files

def chunk_lines(text: str, chunk_size: int, overlap: int) -> List[Tuple[int, int, str]]:
    lines = text.splitlines()
    chunks = []
    start = 0
    chunk_index = 0

    while start < len(lines):
        end = min(start + chunk_size, len(lines))
        chunk_text = "\n".join(lines[start:end]).strip()
        if chunk_text:
            chunks.append((start + 1, end, chunk_text))
        if end == len(lines):
            break
        start += chunk_size - overlap
        chunk_index += 1

    return chunks

def embedding_to_blob(vec: np.ndarray) -> bytes:
    vec = np.asarray(vec, dtype=np.float32)
    return vec.tobytes()

def index_repository(repo_path: str):
    repo_root = Path(repo_path).resolve()
    conn = sqlite3.connect(DB_PATH)
    init_db(conn)

    model = SentenceTransformer(MODEL_NAME)

    files = walk_files(repo_root)
    print(f"Found {len(files)} files to index")

    inserted = 0

    for file_path in files:
        try:
            text = file_path.read_text(encoding="utf-8", errors="ignore")
        except Exception as e:
            print(f"Skipping {file_path}: {e}")
            continue

        chunks = chunk_lines(text, CHUNK_SIZE, CHUNK_OVERLAP)
        if not chunks:
            continue

        chunk_texts = [chunk_text for _, _, chunk_text in chunks]
        embeddings = model.encode(chunk_texts, normalize_embeddings=True)

        for idx, ((start_line, end_line, chunk_text), emb) in enumerate(zip(chunks, embeddings)):
            content_hash = sha1_text(chunk_text)
            try:
                conn.execute("""
                    INSERT OR IGNORE INTO chunks
                    (file_path, chunk_index, start_line, end_line, content, content_hash, embedding)
                    VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)
                """, (
                    str(file_path.relative_to(repo_root)),
                    idx,
                    start_line,
                    end_line,
                    chunk_text,
                    content_hash,
                    embedding_to_blob(emb)
                ))
                inserted += 1
            except Exception as e:
                print(f"Failed to insert chunk from {file_path}: {e}")

    conn.commit()
    conn.close()
    print(f"Indexing complete. Inserted up to {inserted} chunks.")

if __name__ == "__main__":
    import sys

    if len(sys.argv) != 2:
        print("Usage: python index_codebase.py /path/to/repository")
        raise SystemExit(1)

    index_repository(sys.argv[1])

⸻

What this script does

It scans a repository and stores each chunk in a table called chunks.

Each row contains:

• file_path
• chunk_index
• line range
• chunk content
• content hash
• embedding as bytes

The embedding model all-MiniLM-L6-v2 is compact and fast enough for local indexing. It is not code-specific, but it performs surprisingly well for mixed code and documentation search.

If you want stronger code retrieval later, you can swap the model with one trained for code or technical text.

⸻

Step 2 — Build the search tool

Now we need a query script that:

• embeds the query
• loads vectors from SQLite
• computes cosine similarity
• returns the best matches

